description.narrative: AMAL - Supporting Womens Transformative Leadership in Changing Times and democratic transition 2012-2015 is a SIDA funded 3-year programme. It is a MENA regional project and is implemented in OPT, Morocco, Tunisia and Yemen. The programme is led by OxfamGB (OGB) at regional level with the Programme Management Unit (PMU) located in Beirut, Lebanon. Funding is routed via OGB and the Oxfam Novib(ONL) office reports to the PMU. In the OPT, the project is being implemented by four local partner organizations, three in the West Bank and one in Gaza. The overall objective of the project is: women in OPT region, including poor and marginalised women, have increased ability to participate and exercise leadership at all levels of decision-making, gaining power over their lives and ensuringtheir practical needs and rights are central for existing and emerging governance structures. The project aims to achieve the following four objectives. Objective 1: Rights and Leadership: Palestinian women and youth from marginalized areas in the West Bank and Gaza Strip have increased awareness of their political and socio economic rights and are more confident to voice their rights and play leadership roles at all levels (household, community, national and regional). Objective 2: Capacity-Building: A diversity of Palestinian womens organizations and their allies in the West Bank and Gaza Strip will have increased skills, resources and capacity to advocate a womens rights agenda with a collective voice and influence decision-making. Objective 3: Changing Attitudes and policy: Decision-makers and opinion formers in the OPT including religious and community leaders, journalists, political parties, male politicians at all levels are more aware of their positions and more reflective of the needs and priorities of Palestinian women. Objective4: Linking and Learning: Oxfam, its partners and their allies generate and share knowledge, to strengthen womens participation and leadership approaches in the OPT, region and globally. Direct beneficiaries targeted include youth, women, students, religious and community leaders, journalists, PLC representatives and women members and employees from NGOs, CBOs, political parties, municipalities and trade unions. Representatives of womens rights defenders networks and members of youth, Human rights, trade unions, media personnel are also targeted. The project will reach approximately 6000 direct beneficiaries and 31,000 indirect beneficiaries.

participating-org.narrative:
Oxfam Novib has been active in the Occupied Palestinian Territory/Israel (OPT/I) since 1982 and working with Palestinian refugees in Lebanon since the mid 1980s. It has built up a strong network of relationships with local NGOs and counts among its localcounterparts some of the largest and most professional NGOs in various sectors. It has accompanied these NGOs in their development from ad hoc volunteer groups to sizeable professional institutions with national outreach. At the same time the conceptualisation of the programme has evolved from three country programs in the early 1990s to a program for Palestinians in the Middle East (PME) working withPalestinians in OPT, Israel and Lebanon.
The programme has changed over the years with the establishment of the Palestinian Authority (PA) in the mid-1990s from a focus on support and service provision at a grassroots level and grassroots mobilization, to working towards influencing the establishment of the PA, its lawmaking and supporting building a democratic state # this involved supporting efforts of Palestinian civil society to build the basis for a democratic Palestinian state with room for civil participation, ensuring inclusion of vulnerable groups, refugees and women, and shaping its laws and systems. Oxfam Novib has also supported partners that are working on the provision of humanitarian assistance, response preparedness and conflict transformation. We have also supported partners in the provision of health services, access to quality education and gender justice.
